A story from my anthropologist friend. He was at a small village, interviewing an old metalsmith for purposes of ethnography.

The smith, years ago, was ill, so a doctor was called and he brought him a packet of pills. The poor man did not know better so he took them all at once

just put his back on it and relaxed, knowing his incoming death. The wall opened as a secret door, and he tripped backwards, with it closing behind him. He was on the other side. A man with a white beard asked him "Where are you going?". "To see my uncle" - responded the smith.

His uncle was, in real life, dead. The smith continued, in his vision, to walk forwards, but the path became somehow bright and white, with nature turning more beautiful. Around the path were trees, and under the trees - groups of people. He saw in one group his uncle and went...

to talk to him. The uncle was horrified - "What are you doing here?" - he asked. He had never seen the other people near his uncle, but they looked familiar. The uncle proceeded to tell the smith that he does not belong there, and to turn back and return home.

As the smith turned back, he immediately woke up. He was alive, recovered, and is still alive.

This is a great example of a Near Death Experience, a man getting a glimpse of the otherworldly, but expressed through a national folkloric psychological matrix. May we remember this.
